{"title_page": "Terry Lenzner", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Terry Falk Lenzner\n| image         =\n| image_size    =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1939}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = April 23, 2020\n| death_place   = Washington, DC\n| death_cause   = \n| residence     = \n| nationality   = United States\n| other_names   = \n| known_for     = Founder of Investigative Group International\n| education     = B.A. [[Harvard University]]<br>J.D. [[Harvard Law School]]\n| networth      = \n| occupation    = Attorney\n| spouse        = Margaret Rood\n| children      = \n| parents       =\n| relations     = \n| website       = \n}}\n\n'''Terry F. Lenzner''' (1939-4/23/2020) is an American attorney and founder of Investigative Group International.\n\n==Biography==\nLenzner was raised in a secular [[American Jews|Jewish]] family in [[Manhattan]] and attended [[Philips Exeter Academy]].<ref name=Investigator>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sBC-FsLS3fUC&pg=PT8&lpg=PT8&dq=Jeish#v=onepage&q=Jewish&f=false|first=Lenzner|last=Terry|authorlink=|title=The Investigator|pages= |publisher=|date=June 8, 2005|ISBN=}}</ref> He graduated with a B.A. from [[Harvard University]] and with a J.D. from [[Harvard Law School]].<ref name=BSSleuth>{{Cite web|last= Baer |first= Susan |authorlink=   |title=Clinton's detective has high-profile past Terry F. Lenzner, ex-federal lawyer, now top hired sleuth |publisher=[[Baltimore Sun]]|date=February 28, 1998 |url= http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1998-02-28/news/1998059001_1_lenzner-clinton-independent-counsel |accessdate=}}</ref> After school in 1964, following the advice of attorney [[Lloyd K. Garrison]],<ref name=Investigator /> he worked for the civil rights division of the Justice Department where he investigated the murders of [[Murders of Chaney, Goodman, and Schwerner|three civil rights workers]] in [[Mississippi]].<ref name=BSSleuth /> He then worked as an assistant U.S. attorney under [[Bob Morgenthau]] in the organized crime unit in New York before becoming the director of the federal office of Legal Services in the [[Richard Nixon]] administration.<ref name=BSSleuth /> In 1971, he served on a team under U.S. Attorney General [[Ramsey Clark]] that defended the [[Harrisburg Seven]] and in 1973, under [[Samuel Dash]], as the chief counsel on the [[Senate Watergate Committee]].<ref name=BSSleuth />\n\n===Investigative Group International===\nIn 1984, he founded Investigative Group International, an investigation agency with seven offices in the US as well as in London, [[Sydney, Australia]], and [[Wiesbaden, Germany]].<ref name=BSSleuth /> IGI activities range from conducting background investigations, corporate takeovers, internal fraud investigations and \"opposition research\".<ref name=BSSleuth /> In 1994, the law firm of [[Williams & Connolly]], which was representing President [[Bill Clinton]], retained his firm to investigate the source of the financing for [[Paula Jones]]' sexual misconduct lawsuit against the president.<ref name=BSSleuth /> President Clinton also used the firm to investigate monies contributed by [[1996 United States campaign finance controversy#Major fund-raising figures|Yah Lin \"Charlie\" Trie to Clinton's legal defense fund]].<ref name=BSSleuth />\n\nAlthough he has done work for Republicans at times, he has mostly done work for Democrats and is a close personal friend to Clinton lawyer [[Mickey Kantor]]. Several former IGI employees have links to the Clinton administration including [[Ricki Seidman]]; Interior Department official [[Brooke Shearer]] (wife of Clinton's [[United States Deputy Secretary of State]], [[Strobe Talbott]]); undersecretary of the Treasury [[Raymond W. Kelly]], and Howard Shapiro, general counsel to the FBI.<ref name=BSSleuth /> Independent counsel [[Kenneth W. Starr]] subpoenaed Lenzner (along with [[Sidney Blumenthal]]) regarding allegations that his firm was paid to find negative information regarding Starr's team and possibly \"[[Obstruction of justice|obstructing justice]]\"; after failing to demonstrate [[attorney\u2013client privilege]], Lenzner testified that his firm was doing \"nothing inappropriate\" with the research he was doing for Clinton.<ref name=BSSleuth /><ref name=NYTWhisper>{{Cite web|last=Van Natta Jr.  |first=Don  |authorlink=   |title= Whispering Campaign Was Prod for Subpoenas  |publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=February 25, 1998 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1998/02/25/us/whispering-campaign-was-prod-for-subpoenas.html |accessdate=}}</ref> In 1994, The Clinton administration was criticized for awarding IGI a no-bid grant from the State Department to train police officers in Haiti (sending its then president, former New York City police chief, [[Raymond Kelly]]).<ref name=BSSleuth />\n\nOver the years he has been retained by numerous high profile clients to conduction opposition research. In 1991, the firm was retained in investigating [[United Way]] president [[William Aramony]].<ref name=BSSleuth /> Also in 1991, [[Mike Tyson]] used the firm to investigate the activities of his accusers and whether his jurors acted appropriately.<ref name=BSSleuth /> In 1994, he was retained by Senator [[Ted Kennedy]] to investigate his opponent which stoked some controversy when the Kennedy campaign denied employing the firm and when no record of payments to IGI were found, it was discovered that Washington lawyer [[James Flug]] had hired IGI and was reimbursed by the campaign.<ref name=WPPrivateEye>{{Cite web|last=Ringle  |first= Ken |authorlink=   |title=Lenzner: Private Eye Or Public Enemy?   |publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=March 2, 1998 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/lenzner030298.htm  |accessdate=}}</ref> In 1993, he was hired by tobacco giant [[Brown & Williamson]] to investigate [[whistleblower]] [[Jeffrey Wigand]].<ref name=WPPrivateEye /> In 1997, the [[Democratic National Committee]] used IGI to audit political contributions.<ref name=BSSleuth />  In 1996, [[United States Senate election in Maine, 1996|Republican Senate candidate]] [[Robert Monks]] hired him to investigate his opponent's alleged sexual assault.<ref name=BSSleuth /> In 1997, Lenzner was asked to find derogatory information on Republican Senator [[Don Nickles]] and his wife;<ref name=NYTWhisper /> Senator [[Joseph Lieberman]] criticized Lenzner's tactics as an \"intrusion into the system.\"<ref name=BSSleuth /> [[Ivana Trump]] hired him to investigate [[Donald Trump's]] relationship with [[Marla Maples]] and to determine his financial assets.<ref name=BSSleuth /><ref>{{Cite web|last=Blomquist  |first=Brian  |authorlink=   |title=Gumshoe's Reputation is All Heel and No Soul - Prober of Prez Works With Greatest of Sleaze   |publisher=[[New York Post]]|date= July 18, 2000 |url=https://nypost.com/2000/07/18/gumshoes-reputation-is-all-heel-and-no-soul-prober-for-prez-works-with-greatest-of-sleaze/  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLenzner is married to Margaret Rood Lenzner; they have three children: Jonathan Lenzner, Emily Lenzner Cherukuri, and William Lenzner. His son Jonathan is married to [[Washington Post]] writer [[Matea Gold]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=  |first=  |authorlink=   |title= Matea Gold, Jonathan Lenzner  |publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=August 27, 2006 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/27/fashion/weddings/27gold.html |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=  |first=  |authorlink=   |title= Emily Lenzner and Peter Cherukuri |publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=September 30, 2007 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/30/fashion/weddings/30LENZNER.html|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lenzner, Terry}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Phillips Academy alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Terry Falk Lenzner\n| image         =\n| image_size    =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1939}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = 2020-04-23\n| death_place   = Washington, DC\n| death_cause   = \n| residence     = \n| nationality   = United States\n| other_names   = \n| known_for     = Founder of Investigative Group International\n| education     = B.A. [[Harvard University]]<br>J.D. [[Harvard Law School]]\n| networth      = \n| occupation    = Attorney\n| spouse        = Margaret Rood\n| children      = \n| parents       =\n| relations     = \n| website       = \n}}\n\n'''Terry F. Lenzner''' (1939-4/23/2020) is an American attorney and founder of Investigative Group International.\n\n==Biography==\nLenzner was raised in a secular [[American Jews|Jewish]] family in [[Manhattan]] and attended [[Philips Exeter Academy]].<ref name=Investigator>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sBC-FsLS3fUC&pg=PT8&lpg=PT8&dq=Jeish#v=onepage&q=Jewish&f=false|first=Lenzner|last=Terry|authorlink=|title=The Investigator|pages= |publisher=|date=June 8, 2005|ISBN=}}</ref> He graduated with a B.A. from [[Harvard University]] and with a J.D. from [[Harvard Law School]].<ref name=BSSleuth>{{Cite web|last= Baer |first= Susan |authorlink=   |title=Clinton's detective has high-profile past Terry F. Lenzner, ex-federal lawyer, now top hired sleuth |publisher=[[Baltimore Sun]]|date=February 28, 1998 |url= http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1998-02-28/news/1998059001_1_lenzner-clinton-independent-counsel |accessdate=}}</ref> After school in 1964, following the advice of attorney [[Lloyd K. Garrison]],<ref name=Investigator /> he worked for the civil rights division of the Justice Department where he investigated the murders of [[Murders of Chaney, Goodman, and Schwerner|three civil rights workers]] in [[Mississippi]].<ref name=BSSleuth /> He then worked as an assistant U.S. attorney under [[Bob Morgenthau]] in the organized crime unit in New York before becoming the director of the federal office of Legal Services in the [[Richard Nixon]] administration.<ref name=BSSleuth /> In 1971, he served on a team under U.S. Attorney General [[Ramsey Clark]] that defended the [[Harrisburg Seven]] and in 1973, under [[Samuel Dash]], as the chief counsel on the [[Senate Watergate Committee]].<ref name=BSSleuth />\n\n===Investigative Group International===\nIn 1984, he founded Investigative Group International, an investigation agency with seven offices in the US as well as in London, [[Sydney, Australia]], and [[Wiesbaden, Germany]].<ref name=BSSleuth /> IGI activities range from conducting background investigations, corporate takeovers, internal fraud investigations and \"opposition research\".<ref name=BSSleuth /> In 1994, the law firm of [[Williams & Connolly]], which was representing President [[Bill Clinton]], retained his firm to investigate the source of the financing for [[Paula Jones]]' sexual misconduct lawsuit against the president.<ref name=BSSleuth /> President Clinton also used the firm to investigate monies contributed by [[1996 United States campaign finance controversy#Major fund-raising figures|Yah Lin \"Charlie\" Trie to Clinton's legal defense fund]].<ref name=BSSleuth />\n\nAlthough he has done work for Republicans at times, he has mostly done work for Democrats and is a close personal friend to Clinton lawyer [[Mickey Kantor]]. Several former IGI employees have links to the Clinton administration including [[Ricki Seidman]]; Interior Department official [[Brooke Shearer]] (wife of Clinton's [[United States Deputy Secretary of State]], [[Strobe Talbott]]); undersecretary of the Treasury [[Raymond W. Kelly]], and Howard Shapiro, general counsel to the FBI.<ref name=BSSleuth /> Independent counsel [[Kenneth W. Starr]] subpoenaed Lenzner (along with [[Sidney Blumenthal]]) regarding allegations that his firm was paid to find negative information regarding Starr's team and possibly \"[[Obstruction of justice|obstructing justice]]\"; after failing to demonstrate [[attorney\u2013client privilege]], Lenzner testified that his firm was doing \"nothing inappropriate\" with the research he was doing for Clinton.<ref name=BSSleuth /><ref name=NYTWhisper>{{Cite web|last=Van Natta Jr.  |first=Don  |authorlink=   |title= Whispering Campaign Was Prod for Subpoenas  |publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=February 25, 1998 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1998/02/25/us/whispering-campaign-was-prod-for-subpoenas.html |accessdate=}}</ref> In 1994, The Clinton administration was criticized for awarding IGI a no-bid grant from the State Department to train police officers in Haiti (sending its then president, former New York City police chief, [[Raymond Kelly]]).<ref name=BSSleuth />\n\nOver the years he has been retained by numerous high profile clients to conduction opposition research. In 1991, the firm was retained in investigating [[United Way]] president [[William Aramony]].<ref name=BSSleuth /> Also in 1991, [[Mike Tyson]] used the firm to investigate the activities of his accusers and whether his jurors acted appropriately.<ref name=BSSleuth /> In 1994, he was retained by Senator [[Ted Kennedy]] to investigate his opponent which stoked some controversy when the Kennedy campaign denied employing the firm and when no record of payments to IGI were found, it was discovered that Washington lawyer [[James Flug]] had hired IGI and was reimbursed by the campaign.<ref name=WPPrivateEye>{{Cite web|last=Ringle  |first= Ken |authorlink=   |title=Lenzner: Private Eye Or Public Enemy?   |publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=March 2, 1998 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/lenzner030298.htm  |accessdate=}}</ref> In 1993, he was hired by tobacco giant [[Brown & Williamson]] to investigate [[whistleblower]] [[Jeffrey Wigand]].<ref name=WPPrivateEye /> In 1997, the [[Democratic National Committee]] used IGI to audit political contributions.<ref name=BSSleuth />  In 1996, [[United States Senate election in Maine, 1996|Republican Senate candidate]] [[Robert Monks]] hired him to investigate his opponent's alleged sexual assault.<ref name=BSSleuth /> In 1997, Lenzner was asked to find derogatory information on Republican Senator [[Don Nickles]] and his wife;<ref name=NYTWhisper /> Senator [[Joseph Lieberman]] criticized Lenzner's tactics as an \"intrusion into the system.\"<ref name=BSSleuth /> [[Ivana Trump]] hired him to investigate [[Donald Trump's]] relationship with [[Marla Maples]] and to determine his financial assets.<ref name=BSSleuth /><ref>{{Cite web|last=Blomquist  |first=Brian  |authorlink=   |title=Gumshoe's Reputation is All Heel and No Soul - Prober of Prez Works With Greatest of Sleaze   |publisher=[[New York Post]]|date= July 18, 2000 |url=https://nypost.com/2000/07/18/gumshoes-reputation-is-all-heel-and-no-soul-prober-for-prez-works-with-greatest-of-sleaze/  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLenzner is married to Margaret Rood Lenzner; they have three children: Jonathan Lenzner, Emily Lenzner Cherukuri, and William Lenzner. His son Jonathan is married to [[Washington Post]] writer [[Matea Gold]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=  |first=  |authorlink=   |title= Matea Gold, Jonathan Lenzner  |publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=August 27, 2006 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/27/fashion/weddings/27gold.html |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=  |first=  |authorlink=   |title= Emily Lenzner and Peter Cherukuri |publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=September 30, 2007 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/30/fashion/weddings/30LENZNER.html|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lenzner, Terry}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Univer